# Why We Built LATERALUS

@meta {
  title: "Why We Built LATERALUS — A Language That Thinks Like You Do"
  date: "2024-11-01"
  author: "bad-antics"
  tags: ["philosophy", "design", "pipelines", "science"]
  reading_time: "8 min"
}

@heading level=1 {
  Why We Built LATERALUS
}

@paragraph {
  There's a moment every programmer recognizes. You're working through a data
  transformation — filter this, map that, fold it down to a result — and you
  find yourself writing either a deeply nested function call that reads
  right-to-left, or a parade of temporary variables that exist only to be
  immediately discarded.
}

@paragraph {
  Neither feels right. Neither matches how you *thought* about the problem.
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  // How you have to write it
  let result = sum(map(filter(numbers, is_even), square))

  // How you actually thought about it
  let result = numbers |> filter(is_even) |> map(square) |> sum()
}

@paragraph {
  That gap — between thinking and expressing — is what LATERALUS was built to close.
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  The Pipeline Operator Was Always the Point
}

@paragraph {
  The @code{|>} operator exists in Elixir, F#, Elm, and now has a proposal in
  JavaScript. But in LATERALUS, it isn't a library feature or a syntax sugar
  bolted on afterward. It's the *primary* abstraction. Everything in the
  language design flows from it.
}

@paragraph {
  When data flows left-to-right through named transformations, code becomes
  readable in the same direction as thought. You don't have to mentally
  parse inside-out. The program becomes a narrative.
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  // Text analysis — reads exactly like the algorithm
  let keywords = corpus
    |> split_sentences()
    |> flat_map(tokenize)
    |> filter(is_content_word)
    |> map(stem)
    |> frequency_count()
    |> sort_by_value(descending: true)
    |> take(50)
}

@paragraph {
  That's not a clever trick. That's the code *being* the algorithm.
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  Scientists Deserve Better Tools
}

@paragraph {
  Most scientific computing happens in Python with NumPy and SciPy, or in
  MATLAB, or in Julia. These are excellent tools. But they weren't *designed*
  around the mental model of scientific work.
}

@paragraph {
  In scientific work, you think in units. You think in physical constants.
  You think in equations that have names. When you write @code{E = m * c^2},
  you don't want to look up what @code{2.998e8} is — you want @code{SPEED_OF_LIGHT}.
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  import "science"

  // CODATA 2018 physical constants, built in
  let E_rest = ELECTRON_MASS * SPEED_OF_LIGHT ** 2
  let lambda  = PLANCK / (ELECTRON_MASS * velocity)

  // ODE solver — one line
  let trajectory = solve_ode(gravity_eqn, y0=pos, t0=0, t1=100, steps=10000)

  // FFT — one line
  let spectrum = signal |> fft() |> power_spectrum()
}

@paragraph {
  LATERALUS has CODATA 2018 physical constants as named identifiers.
  It has an RK4 ODE solver. It has FFT. It has statistical distributions.
  Not as libraries you install — as part of the language.
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  Mathematical Elegance Without Mathematical Verbosity
}

@paragraph {
  Julia made a compelling argument: if you make mathematical notation natural,
  scientists will write better code. LATERALUS agrees, but pushes further:
  what if *all* code — not just the math — had that elegance?
}

@paragraph {
  This is why LATERALUS has automatic differentiation built into the math engine.
  You shouldn't need to manually derive gradients in a programming language.
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  // Dual numbers for automatic differentiation
  let f = (x) => x ** 3 + 2 * x ** 2 - x + 5

  // Exact derivative at x=2 — no numerical approximation
  let df_dx = auto_diff(f, 2.0)  // = 3x² + 4x - 1 at x=2 = 19.0
}

@paragraph {
  And this is why the matrix operations feel natural:
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  let A = matrix([[1, 2], [3, 4]])
  let B = matrix([[5, 6], [7, 8]])

  let C = A @ B          // matrix multiply
  let d = determinant(A) // -2.0
  let e = eigenvalues(A) // [-0.372, 5.372]
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  The Tool That Inspired the Name
}

@paragraph {
  The language is named after the Tool album *Lateralus*. The album is built
  around the Fibonacci sequence — the time signatures of the title track literally
  spell out 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13. It's mathematics expressed as music.
}

@paragraph {
  The lyric that defines the project:
}

@quote {
  "Spiral out. Keep going."
}

@paragraph {
  That's the philosophy. A good language doesn't constrain you — it gives you
  a foundation to spiral outward from. Start simple. Build complexity. Return
  to the core principles. Keep going.
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  What Comes Next
}

@paragraph {
  Version 1.3.0 is the ecosystem release. The math engine, crypto engine,
  science module, LSP server, debugger, formatter, linter, package manager,
  and VS Code extension are all now part of the standard distribution.
}

@paragraph {
  The v2 compiler is being written in LATERALUS itself. When it compiles itself
  for the first time, the language will have achieved the most meaningful
  milestone in any programming language's life: self-hosting.
}

@paragraph {
  Until then: spiral out. Keep going.
}

@footer {
  Filed under: philosophy, design · November 2024
}

